                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">Late 16th – first half of the17th-century script; careful hand. <!----><note>
                           <p>Unknown</p>
                           <!--Unknown-->
                        </note>
                        <note><!--Scribal Practices - In order to accommodate longer text lines, the scribe employed compressed script, fol. 36r  - The so-called traditional titles of the Ethiopic Psalms are missing but for the first and the last Psalm - The Ethiopic word for “king” is consequently spelled nǝgwǝś, ንጕሥ (e.g., fols. 23r, 25r, 53v, 54r, 100v, 173r, etc.), not as the standard form nǝguś (ንጉሥ). -->
                           <p>- In order to accommodate longer text lines, the scribe employed compressed script, fol. <locus target="#36r"/>
                           </p>
                           <p>- The so-called traditional titles of the Ethiopic Psalms are missing but for the first and the last Psalm</p>
                           <p>- The Ethiopic word for “king” is consequently spelled nǝgwǝś, ንጕሥ (e.g., fols. <locus target="#23r #25r #53v #54r #100v #173r"/>etc.), not as the standard form nǝguś (ንጉሥ). </p>
                        </note>
